											<td width="100%" valign="top">					
												<!-- START NEWS AREAS-->
												<table width="90%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
													<tr><td valign="top" width="100%">&nbsp;<br>
													<!-- strMainData goes here-->
													<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='header' bgcolor='black' width='100%'>PALADIN STRATEGIES AND PLAYGUIDES</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='spti'>STRATEGIES FOR THE 30+ PALADIN</font> - <small>Nidrev Nathanael, Tunare</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>Hail, holy warrior!  You've endured everything that Norrath has thrown at you so far, and you've just gotten your level 30 spells and are ready to go take on the world.  Well take a breath adventurer, the ride gets a little tougher.  :)  <p> <p>

First off, you have to realize that to gain any significant amount of experience beyond 30, you are not going to do it alone.  Paladins are not meant to be solo players, so the first piece of advice is:  Group!  Group!  Group!  Where?  There are several places to be, notably Solusek A, Unrest, deep in Upper Guk, and a few spots in Mistmoore (if you're daring).  At higher levels, you'll move into Solusek B, Lower Guk, deep Mistmoore, planes, and Kedge Keep.<p> <p>

Realize, that in a group, you play a couple roles.  You will be a secondary tank in a group with a warrior, and it is good to spread the damage around, so use your taunt skill as much as possible.  In a group without a warrior, a paladin should be the primary tank.  Having more HP's than rangers, and wanting to leave room for rangers to cast spells, you want mobs to be on you.  Until level 39, your heals probably won't save anyone's life in a critical situation, and you should almost always attack your target.  Use your heals to reduce downtime.  At level 39, you can heal just as well as a druid or shaman, and may find yourself being primary healer in a few groups.  Be prepared to play the cleric at that level. <p> <p>

There are 2 ways to make a group really like you.  The first is judicious use of Lay Hands.  Don't just save it for yourself.  Many times, by using Lay Hands to save your warrior or evac'er, you save the group.  It's a great taunt, which can be a blessing in disguise.  Don't be selfish with Lay Hands.  Learn when to use it on others in sticky situations, and people will learn to like Paladins really quickly.  <p> <p>

The other way I have found to stand out in a group is to become a master of spell interruption.  Paladins are almost the only melee class that use shields at high levels, and they are great assets with the ability to bash.  Also, during combat, the spell I use most is Stun.  Interrupting a mob while casting becomes ever increasingly important at higher levels, when you encounter mobs that can complete heal themselves (or others) and can nuke your teammates for several hundred damage at a time, or even charm a member of your group.  Stuns are also great ways to take mobs out of the fight.  Each time a stun lands, that's a few seconds that your group is doing damage and the mob is not.  It adds up over time, and is actually a highly efficient use of your mana during combat, which typically doesn't get used a lot.  (Yaulp doesn't count :P)  Also, keep in mind that Stun can be a great way to stop runners. <p> <p>

Of course, at level 39, the addition of Greater Heal to your spell arsenal is a tremendous boon.  It makes your class a little more difficult to play, because you will find yourself learning when to stop your attack during combat to heal others, something that you haven't done a great deal before (hopefully).  Learning to heal is a skill all its own, and you will join the ranks of clerics, druids, and shamen in your value to a group.  Fear the melee class that can heal! <p> <p>

As far as equipment goes, it's kind of your call as to what you want.  I typically have gone for more melee stats than for mana, which means lots of +AC, +STR, and +HP.  A lot of 39+ paladins like to have two separate sets of armor they wear: one for melee, and one for mana.  I will suggest that on high-level raids on dragons and planes and such, since clerics are essential to such endeavors anyways, to gear yourself towards melee stats.  While you will not necessarily do more damage than a warrior, ranger, or monk, the damage you can dish out is very significant, and you will be able to soak up the damage just as well, if not better.  Many times, by not dying, you win.  And that's what paladins can do better than any other melee class.  :)  <p> <p>

As a whole, paladins bring their own set of unique abilities to the table.  They are not warriors.  They are not rangers.  They are not clerics.  They are paladins, and a good paladin will be welcomed in many groups.  Good fortune, and safe hunting!<p> <p>

Nidrev Nathanael<p>
Paladin, Tunare Server
</td></tr>
